WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:04.870 --> 00:00:08.107
Mike Demopoulos: Hello and
welcome to the 2 o'clock hour

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:12.845
UTC of WP
Accessibility Day 2020.

00:00:12.878 --> 00:00:15.681
I'm your host, Mike Demo,
and I am so excited

00:00:15.714 --> 00:00:18.184
about today: the
next presentation.

00:00:18.217 --> 00:00:20.653
But before we get to that, a
little bit of housekeeping.

00:00:20.686 --> 00:00:23.423
First of all, remember that
we are a welcoming community,

00:00:23.456 --> 00:00:26.492
and the code of conduct is
enforced in all areas of the

00:00:26.525 --> 00:00:28.694
experience, including the chat.

00:00:28.727 --> 00:00:30.830
And that chat's important
because that's where you put the

00:00:30.863 --> 00:00:34.100
questions, and our wonderful
moderators will click them for

00:00:34.133 --> 00:00:36.669
me to ask after
the presentation.

00:00:36.702 --> 00:00:41.174
Please make sure to follow us
on Twitter @WPAccessibility,

00:00:41.207 --> 00:00:45.678
and our two hashtags are
#wpaccessibilityday

00:00:45.711 --> 00:00:49.782
and #wpad2020.

00:00:49.815 --> 00:00:53.653
It is--up next, we have
Christina Workman.

00:00:53.686 --> 00:00:56.489
Christina Workman is a
support technician at

00:00:56.522 --> 00:00:59.225
WebDevStudios and Maintainn.

00:00:59.258 --> 00:01:01.594
As an advocate for
contributing to WordPress,

00:01:01.627 --> 00:01:05.331
she recently launched the
wp_contribute() podcast and

00:01:05.364 --> 00:01:09.035
helps organize WordCamp US,
WordCamp Calgary, and the

00:01:09.068 --> 00:01:11.037
Calgary WordPress Meetup.

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:13.840
She has a passion for teaching
kids STEM and improving

00:01:13.873 --> 00:01:15.608
her accessibility skills.

00:01:15.641 --> 00:01:19.779
Outside of WordPress,
Christina is a purple-o-phile,

00:01:19.812 --> 00:01:24.484
tea fanatic, and lover of
British detective shows.

00:01:24.517 --> 00:01:28.588
So, with that, it is my pleasure
to welcome my friend Christina.

00:01:28.888 --> 00:01:32.125
Christina Workman: Hi, Mike.
Thanks.

00:01:32.158 --> 00:01:34.828
All right, let me
just get the slides.

00:01:35.495 --> 00:01:37.130
All right.
Hi, everyone.

00:01:37.163 --> 00:01:40.066
Thanks for joining me for
our accessibility--sorry.

00:01:40.099 --> 00:01:43.402
Accessible Websites
Benefit Everyone.

00:01:43.435 --> 00:01:45.771
First, a little bit about me:
I know Mike already sort of

00:01:45.804 --> 00:01:48.608
touched on a lot
of these points.

00:01:48.641 --> 00:01:52.645
But I do have a podcast
called wp_contribute(),

00:01:52.678 --> 00:01:54.514
where I interview people
who contribute

00:01:54.547 --> 00:01:56.549
to the WordPress Project.

00:01:56.582 --> 00:02:00.153
I've been a Meetup and WordCamp
organizer for several years.

00:02:00.186 --> 00:02:02.722
And a good chunk of everything
that I have learned about

00:02:02.755 --> 00:02:06.359
WordPress, I have learned
at these kinds of events.

00:02:06.392 --> 00:02:09.829
I've been using WordPress
for about ten years now,

00:02:09.862 --> 00:02:13.366
first as a freelancer and then,
as Mike said, a support

00:02:13.399 --> 00:02:18.471
technician at the Maintainn
Division for WebDevStudios.

00:02:18.504 --> 00:02:21.641
I love tea and have at least
a hundred different kinds

00:02:21.674 --> 00:02:23.776
of tea in my kitchen.

00:02:23.809 --> 00:02:26.145
And as Mike said,
I'm a purple-o-phile.

00:02:26.178 --> 00:02:28.614
I am obsessed with
all things purple,

00:02:28.647 --> 00:02:31.584
as you can probably tell
from my slides and my shirt,

00:02:31.617 --> 00:02:34.453
and, you know, if you
see my headphones.

00:02:34.486 --> 00:02:35.821
So yeah.

00:02:35.854 --> 00:02:39.592
I'm still a little bit of
an accessibility newbie;

00:02:39.625 --> 00:02:43.262
maybe about two years ago, I
started to learn about and

00:02:43.295 --> 00:02:46.065
consider accessibility
for websites.

00:02:46.098 --> 00:02:49.602
But even in that short time,
I've noticed that a lot of

00:02:49.635 --> 00:02:54.173
people still have a lot of
apprehension about making sure

00:02:54.206 --> 00:02:56.676
their sites are accessible.

00:02:56.709 --> 00:03:00.780
My goal with this talk is
to help you recognize that

00:03:00.813 --> 00:03:04.450
implementing best practices to
make your website accessible

00:03:04.483 --> 00:03:06.519
will ensure a better
user experience

00:03:06.552 --> 00:03:09.355
for all of your site visitors.

00:03:09.388 --> 00:03:12.191
I'll be discussing
various examples.

00:03:12.224 --> 00:03:17.330
They are by no means exhaustive,
and I hope that you will start

00:03:17.363 --> 00:03:20.466
thinking of your own examples
as we go through these

00:03:20.499 --> 00:03:24.170
and once everything is done.

00:03:24.203 --> 00:03:27.773
So there are lots of reasons
that people give about why they

00:03:27.806 --> 00:03:29.609
won't make their
sites accessible,

00:03:29.642 --> 00:03:32.778
and I'm sure lots of you
have a lot of these already.

00:03:32.811 --> 00:03:37.283
So, the first one, of
course, it costs too much.

00:03:37.316 --> 00:03:40.286
And there are a ton of
counter-arguments to this.

00:03:40.319 --> 00:03:43.155
But essentially, the sooner
you start recognizing and

00:03:43.188 --> 00:03:46.692
considering accessibility,
the less it's going to cost.

00:03:46.725 --> 00:03:50.496
Another one is, it
will wreck my design.

00:03:50.529 --> 00:03:53.199
It might change your design,
but of course, you can still

00:03:53.232 --> 00:03:57.870
make beautiful, creative,
and accessible websites.

00:03:57.903 --> 00:04:00.239
And the third one,
my site visitors

00:04:00.272 --> 00:04:04.243
don't have disabilities.

00:04:04.276 --> 00:04:08.481
This is a giant fallacy which
often goes hand-in-hand with the

00:04:08.514 --> 00:04:12.818
misconception that accessibility
is purely for the sake of people

00:04:12.851 --> 00:04:17.490
with disabilities, and for
some, maybe to avoid lawsuits,

00:04:17.523 --> 00:04:21.027
which is not the right
reason to be doing it.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:25.331
Not only do I guarantee, though,
that your site has visitors who

00:04:25.364 --> 00:04:29.402
have disabilities, I also know
that an accessible website can

00:04:29.435 --> 00:04:33.539
have a positive impact on
anyone who visits that site.

00:04:33.572 --> 00:04:37.510
We need to start understanding
that an accessible website is

00:04:37.543 --> 00:04:43.616
one that can easily
be used by everyone.

00:04:43.649 --> 00:04:48.387
So you might be thinking, how
can I be so sure that your site

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:51.324
has visitors with disabilities?

00:04:51.357 --> 00:04:53.359
The answer is simple.

00:04:53.392 --> 00:04:57.330
We have all experienced
disability, some form

00:04:57.363 --> 00:05:01.467
of disability in our lives,
and we will again.

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:05.471
Often, the image of a person
with a disability is somebody

00:05:05.504 --> 00:05:12.244
who is blind or deaf or has
lost the use of a limb.

00:05:12.277 --> 00:05:15.581
These are considered
permanent disabilities,

00:05:15.614 --> 00:05:20.820
but there are also temporary
and situational disabilities.

00:05:20.853 --> 00:05:27.193
So to put these into context,
if you have an amputated arm,

00:05:27.226 --> 00:05:30.262
that, of course, would be
a permanent disability.

00:05:30.295 --> 00:05:34.333
But a broken arm, which
would be a temporary disability,

00:05:34.366 --> 00:05:38.270
can have the same
impact on how you function.

00:05:38.303 --> 00:05:43.075
And an armful of groceries also
prevents you from using that arm

00:05:43.108 --> 00:05:46.612
for other purposes for a
very short period of time.

00:05:46.645 --> 00:05:49.181
That's situational.

00:05:49.214 --> 00:05:51.751
And there are lots of
accessibility considerations

00:05:51.784 --> 00:05:55.121
that make life easier for people
who aren't experiencing

00:05:55.154 --> 00:05:58.157
any form of disability.

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:00.226
So let's get to some examples.

00:06:00.259 --> 00:06:03.062
And as I said, these are
by no means exhaustive.

00:06:03.095 --> 00:06:05.498
There are a million
different examples,

00:06:05.531 --> 00:06:11.203
and we're not going to touch
on every type of disability,

00:06:11.236 --> 00:06:15.307
but I hope these get
you to start thinking.

00:06:15.340 --> 00:06:17.410
So, first scenario.

00:06:17.443 --> 00:06:20.646
You get home from work and
you have to feed your kids.

00:06:20.679 --> 00:06:22.415
You have a migraine.

00:06:22.448 --> 00:06:26.118
The kids are excited and
loud, which adds to the

00:06:26.151 --> 00:06:28.587
brain fog from your migraine.

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:33.058
You decide to order
delivery from a website.

00:06:33.091 --> 00:06:36.128
So let's discuss some of the
potential barriers that could

00:06:36.161 --> 00:06:45.671
make this a difficult experience
for you in this scenario.

00:06:45.704 --> 00:06:47.540
Confusing navigation.

00:06:47.573 --> 00:06:50.709
Hard-to-find buttons and links.

00:06:50.742 --> 00:06:54.213
These need to be clear where
you're going to click in order

00:06:54.246 --> 00:06:58.184
to get to the ordering portal,
to add items to your cart, to

00:06:58.217 --> 00:07:01.253
pay for your order, all of
these kinds of things.

00:07:01.286 --> 00:07:05.991
Otherwise, you'll end up
getting confused and frustrated.

00:07:06.024 --> 00:07:10.162
Too many calls to action
fighting for your attention when

00:07:10.195 --> 00:07:13.566
you can barely think because of
the migraine and brain fog

00:07:13.599 --> 00:07:15.134
that you have going on.

00:07:15.167 --> 00:07:18.237
These are distractions that
are too hard to cope with.

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:21.373
So again, confusion can ensue.

00:07:21.406 --> 00:07:25.778
Fast-moving animations
similar to too many CTAs,

00:07:25.811 --> 00:07:29.548
but also, these can make your
headache worse and make it hard

00:07:29.581 --> 00:07:33.252
for you to even
look at the screen.

00:07:33.285 --> 00:07:36.388
And finally, some
checkout form issues.

00:07:36.421 --> 00:07:40.726
Input field labels used as
placeholder text that disappear

00:07:40.759 --> 00:07:43.362
when you start
typing in that field.

00:07:43.395 --> 00:07:46.765
I've been caught by these when
I'm not giving my site my full

00:07:46.798 --> 00:07:50.803
attention, even
without a headache.

00:07:50.836 --> 00:07:55.674
Imagine in our scenario,
you click into a field,

00:07:55.707 --> 00:07:58.844
you hear a crash in the
living room that distracts you,

00:07:58.877 --> 00:08:03.082
and when you return back to that
form and return your attention

00:08:03.115 --> 00:08:07.019
there, you have no recollection
of what that input field was for

00:08:07.052 --> 00:08:10.122
and what you are
supposed to enter there.

00:08:10.155 --> 00:08:14.493
And something I see less often
but certainly has happened,

00:08:14.526 --> 00:08:18.697
the inability to click into a
field can baffle and frustrate

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:20.533
and make you think
that it's impossible

00:08:20.566 --> 00:08:23.702
to complete this order.

00:08:23.735 --> 00:08:27.072
All of these factors could
result in you giving up on

00:08:27.105 --> 00:08:29.642
placing an order on
the site and taking

00:08:29.675 --> 00:08:31.577
your business elsewhere.

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:36.515
Not to mention adding to just
the general frustration and

00:08:36.548 --> 00:08:39.785
chaos that's
happening around you.

00:08:39.818 --> 00:08:42.821
Migraines fall under the
neurological category,

00:08:42.854 --> 00:08:46.525
which would include
other things such as ADHD,

00:08:46.558 --> 00:08:51.363
autism, and epilepsy as
permanent disabilities.

00:08:51.396 --> 00:08:57.036
So who else can benefit from
neurological considerations?

00:08:57.069 --> 00:08:59.271
I'm sure you can all
relate to at least

00:08:59.304 --> 00:09:01.540
one of these situations.

00:09:01.573 --> 00:09:05.377
Brain fog, which can happen on
its own or can be a result of a

00:09:05.410 --> 00:09:11.550
lack of sleep or a flu or cold;
mental health concerns like

00:09:11.583 --> 00:09:16.555
anxiety, depression,
even general stress

00:09:16.588 --> 00:09:20.459
can impact your ability to focus
and process what you see on a

00:09:20.492 --> 00:09:26.632
site as well as simply being
in a distracting environment.

00:09:26.665 --> 00:09:33.372
Neurological accessibility
benefits everyone.

00:09:33.405 --> 00:09:36.241
So, our next scenario.

00:09:36.274 --> 00:09:39.478
You decide to remote work
from a local coffee shop.

00:09:39.511 --> 00:09:42.281
I used to do this all the time.

00:09:42.314 --> 00:09:46.452
You get stuck on a problem
and search for a tutorial.

00:09:46.485 --> 00:09:51.357
You find the perfect video
embedded on its own webpage,

00:09:51.390 --> 00:09:55.661
but darn it, you forgot
your headphones at home.

00:09:55.694 --> 00:09:59.231
So what are some
potential complications here?

00:09:59.264 --> 00:10:02.301
First, if there are no
closed captions or subtitling

00:10:02.334 --> 00:10:08.107
available, you can't watch it on
mute and know what's being said.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:11.710
If video is the only way the
information was presented,

00:10:11.743 --> 00:10:14.847
there's no transcript or
blog post that sums up that

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:19.218
information, both of these
results in you being unable to

00:10:19.251 --> 00:10:24.857
get the information that
you need when you need it.

00:10:24.890 --> 00:10:28.827
The last item isn't necessarily
a barrier but definitely has

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:32.798
the potential to cause
issues and embarrassment.

00:10:32.831 --> 00:10:39.271
The video is set to autoplay,
and as soon as the page loads,

00:10:39.304 --> 00:10:43.776
the audio is streaming out of
your laptop for all to hear.

00:10:43.809 --> 00:10:47.279
Personally, I've actually been
startled by autoplaying videos

00:10:47.312 --> 00:10:52.484
before, even on sites
I repeatedly visit.

00:10:52.517 --> 00:10:56.221
These issues are all audio
related and certainly affect

00:10:56.254 --> 00:10:59.625
people who have some form
of permanent hearing loss.

00:10:59.658 --> 00:11:02.661
But there are a variety of other
people who can benefit from text

00:11:02.694 --> 00:11:08.567
alternatives to audio, people
with temporary hearing loss due

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:12.738
to tinnitus or a plugged ear
that could be caused from an ear

00:11:12.771 --> 00:11:16.709
infection or allergies or even
if you've been traveling

00:11:16.742 --> 00:11:19.812
and just got off a plane.

00:11:19.845 --> 00:11:23.615
I often prefer to skim through
text to find a quick answer

00:11:23.648 --> 00:11:26.785
rather than watching a video.

00:11:26.818 --> 00:11:31.256
And some people simply process
information better by reading it

00:11:31.289 --> 00:11:34.193
rather than listening to it.

00:11:34.226 --> 00:11:37.663
People learning a new language
may use subtitles to follow

00:11:37.696 --> 00:11:43.235
along and help them learn and
understand the language better.

00:11:43.268 --> 00:11:46.338
And of course, in this age, we
have digital assistants like

00:11:46.371 --> 00:11:50.476
Siri, Google Assistant, Alexa,
and they can all read text

00:11:50.509 --> 00:11:53.312
from websites if it's there.

00:11:53.345 --> 00:11:55.848
And, of course, loud
environments in general can

00:11:55.881 --> 00:12:00.586
make it very hard to understand
what is being said in audio.

00:12:00.619 --> 00:12:06.158
Audio accessibility
benefits everyone.

00:12:06.191 --> 00:12:09.428
So, our third scenario.

00:12:09.461 --> 00:12:11.697
You're a WordPress
developer who never takes

00:12:11.730 --> 00:12:14.199
their hands off the keyboard.

00:12:14.232 --> 00:12:16.769
You know all the
keyboard shortcuts,

00:12:16.802 --> 00:12:21.573
and there's not a mouse to be
found anywhere in your office.

00:12:21.606 --> 00:12:25.210
You decide to register in an
online course with the latest

00:12:25.243 --> 00:12:29.381
and greatest headless platform.

00:12:29.414 --> 00:12:31.717
So let's look at some of
the barriers you might

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:35.654
experience with this scenario.

00:12:35.687 --> 00:12:39.057
No "Skip to Content" option,
which means you have to tab

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:42.227
through every single item in
the header before getting to

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:44.496
the main part of the page.

00:12:44.529 --> 00:12:46.799
Add to that a main
navigation that forces you

00:12:46.832 --> 00:12:49.601
to tap through every sub item.

00:12:49.634 --> 00:12:54.506
And you may feel like it's never
going to get off of the header.

00:12:54.539 --> 00:12:57.109
No focus indication
means you can't see

00:12:57.142 --> 00:13:00.379
where you are on that page,
what link or button

00:13:00.412 --> 00:13:03.749
you might click if
you hit enter.

00:13:03.782 --> 00:13:07.219
Then we've got unexpected
tab behavior, which can take you

00:13:07.252 --> 00:13:12.357
all over the page in
some random experiences.

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:15.260
And I've seen where it goes
straight from the "Skip to

00:13:15.293 --> 00:13:18.197
Content" right down to the
bottom to the chat box that they

00:13:18.230 --> 00:13:24.436
have, then back up to the
top, and then into the middle,

00:13:24.469 --> 00:13:28.207
and that's just so confusing
when you're trying to follow

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:30.776
the flow of the page.

00:13:30.809 --> 00:13:33.345
And then, by the time you
finally read the information

00:13:33.378 --> 00:13:36.081
about the course and
decide to register,

00:13:36.114 --> 00:13:39.451
you may encounter keyboard traps
like not being able to return to

00:13:39.484 --> 00:13:42.788
a field once it's filled out
or not being able to leave the

00:13:42.821 --> 00:13:46.625
registration form
unless you hit submit.

00:13:46.658 --> 00:13:48.760
These are frustrations
that people with physical

00:13:48.793 --> 00:13:52.130
disabilities, who need to use
keyboards or other special

00:13:52.163 --> 00:13:57.069
devices to navigate
websites, face all the time.

00:13:57.102 --> 00:14:00.038
So here's some other examples of
when you might need or want to

00:14:00.071 --> 00:14:04.276
rely solely on your keyboard.

00:14:04.309 --> 00:14:07.713
You may have a broken arm, a
broken wrist, a broken finger.

00:14:07.746 --> 00:14:12.284
Anything on that limb that
is just not functioning

00:14:12.317 --> 00:14:15.254
or even if it does function.

00:14:15.287 --> 00:14:17.489
I've had my
finger broken before,

00:14:17.522 --> 00:14:19.258
and you get that splint on it.

00:14:19.291 --> 00:14:22.628
And try using a mouse with
a splint on your finger.

00:14:22.661 --> 00:14:25.664
It just doesn't work.

00:14:25.697 --> 00:14:28.667
Maybe you have carpal tunnel
syndrome or something else that

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:33.038
flares up every now,
but not all the time.

00:14:33.071 --> 00:14:36.174
Maybe you have a wireless
mouse, and the battery died

00:14:36.207 --> 00:14:39.511
and you don't have any
extra batteries in the house.

00:14:39.544 --> 00:14:42.180
Or my personal favorite,
you have a sleeping baby

00:14:42.213 --> 00:14:45.183
or pet on your lap.

00:14:45.216 --> 00:14:48.754
My dog loves to sit on my lap
and rest his head on my dominant

00:14:48.787 --> 00:14:53.792
arm, and I hate to disturb
him, so I don't move my arm.

00:14:53.825 --> 00:14:57.863
I just put it in position on the
keyboard and try to type as best

00:14:57.896 --> 00:15:01.767
I can and use my
other hand as well.

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:05.237
So keyboard
accessibility benefits everyone.

00:15:08.306 --> 00:15:10.342
Our last scenario.

00:15:10.375 --> 00:15:13.712
You live in Oregon on the
West Coast in the United States,

00:15:13.745 --> 00:15:16.114
and its three weeks ago.

00:15:16.147 --> 00:15:19.117
Temperatures are high and you
don't have an air conditioner,

00:15:19.150 --> 00:15:21.453
so windows need to be open.

00:15:21.486 --> 00:15:25.724
Wildfires break out all around
you, causing poor air quality

00:15:25.757 --> 00:15:29.795
that irritates your eyes
and blurs your vision.

00:15:29.828 --> 00:15:34.599
You have to evacuate to a more
rural area that has poor wi-fi,

00:15:34.632 --> 00:15:37.035
and you're going to work
remotely while you're there,

00:15:37.068 --> 00:15:41.473
and you need to visit a variety
of websites throughout the day.

00:15:41.506 --> 00:15:43.142
So let's look at
our barriers here.

00:15:44.809 --> 00:15:49.348
When you have blurry eyes,
trying to read small or skinny

00:15:49.381 --> 00:15:53.452
font text is really difficult.

00:15:53.485 --> 00:15:56.588
Low contrast between the
foreground and the background

00:15:56.621 --> 00:15:59.157
can make it hard to see
information when you're trying

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:02.094
to get your eyes to
focus and they won't.

00:16:02.127 --> 00:16:06.398
Linked text can be hard to
notice if it's only using color

00:16:06.431 --> 00:16:08.500
to differentiate
from regular text

00:16:08.533 --> 00:16:11.236
and if the colors
are too similar.

00:16:11.269 --> 00:16:14.272
Maybe you want to zoom in to
make it easier to read the

00:16:14.305 --> 00:16:18.276
content, but the layout
isn't suited to resizing.

00:16:18.309 --> 00:16:22.547
So images and maybe even text
go off the side of the screen,

00:16:22.580 --> 00:16:25.117
and you can't access it.

00:16:25.150 --> 00:16:28.820
And if images don't load because
of the weak wi-fi and there is

00:16:28.853 --> 00:16:31.623
no alternative text, you
could be missing

00:16:31.656 --> 00:16:34.793
out on important information.

00:16:34.826 --> 00:16:37.763
These all fall into the
visual category, affecting

00:16:37.796 --> 00:16:41.800
people who have colorblindness
or reduced vision.

00:16:41.833 --> 00:16:44.636
And again, we have lots of
scenarios that can affect your

00:16:44.669 --> 00:16:48.673
ability to see a website.

00:16:48.706 --> 00:16:51.777
You may have an eye injury,
maybe you had eye surgery

00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:54.146
or an eye infection.

00:16:54.179 --> 00:16:56.581
I heard this mentioned
in another talk earlier,

00:16:56.614 --> 00:17:02.254
you know, there's a typo on this
slide, but the dilated eyes

00:17:02.287 --> 00:17:06.525
from having an eye exam when you
get those drops in your eyes.

00:17:06.558 --> 00:17:10.429
Another form of migraine is an
oral migraine which can cause

00:17:10.462 --> 00:17:14.533
part or all of your
vision to be obscured.

00:17:14.566 --> 00:17:19.037
Bright sun, either shining
directly on your eyes or on your

00:17:19.070 --> 00:17:21.339
screen, can make it hard
to see when the

00:17:21.372 --> 00:17:25.277
contrast isn't very different.

00:17:25.310 --> 00:17:29.748
Allergies similar to the smoke
irritant in our scenario can

00:17:29.781 --> 00:17:34.719
cause your eyes to blur or
maybe something as simple as you

00:17:34.752 --> 00:17:37.689
forgot your reading glasses.

00:17:37.722 --> 00:17:44.529
Visual accessibility
benefits everyone.

00:17:44.562 --> 00:17:47.699
All of these scenarios are
real-life examples, many that

00:17:47.732 --> 00:17:52.304
I have personally experienced
or know somebody who has.

00:17:52.337 --> 00:17:54.806
Maybe you can relate
to one or two of them.

00:17:54.839 --> 00:17:57.776
Maybe you can
relate to a lot of them.

00:17:57.809 --> 00:18:01.646
Either way, I challenge you to
come up with your own examples

00:18:01.679 --> 00:18:05.250
that you can share with others
that will help accessibility

00:18:05.283 --> 00:18:08.520
considerations
become more commonplace.

00:18:08.553 --> 00:18:12.657
And at the very least, I hope I
have convinced you that making

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:19.197
your website accessible
makes it better for everyone.

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:21.766
Thank you for listening.

00:18:21.799 --> 00:18:25.237
You can find me on
Twitter, send me an email,

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:27.506
and of course,
gratuitous plug for my podcast,

00:18:27.539 --> 00:18:32.144
wp_contribute() on all
of the podcast players.

00:18:33.678 --> 00:18:37.048
Mike: Well, that
was a great talk.

00:18:37.081 --> 00:18:45.090
Thank you so much for
taking the time to share that.

00:18:45.123 --> 00:18:47.058
We are waiting for some
questions to come in,

00:18:47.091 --> 00:18:50.128
so if you have any questions,
please put them into the YouTube

00:18:50.161 --> 00:18:53.565
channel and then they'll be
brought over to the webpage

00:18:53.598 --> 00:18:56.268
at wpaccessibilityday.org.

00:18:56.301 --> 00:18:58.637
And you can actually
find Christina's slides

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:01.239
at our website as well.

00:19:01.272 --> 00:19:09.314
But as we're waiting for those
questions to come in, and we do

00:19:09.347 --> 00:19:14.786
have one, I had a--
something that reminded me from

00:19:14.819 --> 00:19:19.491
your talk is I was listening
to someone from Interactive

00:19:19.524 --> 00:19:22.594
Accessibility, and they said
something that when designers

00:19:22.627 --> 00:19:26.164
are put in a box, they
become more creative.

00:19:26.197 --> 00:19:29.134
And I think that's very true.

00:19:29.167 --> 00:19:32.470
And again, this was a while ago
before accessibility was common,

00:19:32.503 --> 00:19:36.274
but your point of, yes, you
can still design pretty things,

00:19:36.307 --> 00:19:39.778
you can still make
interactive applications,

00:19:39.811 --> 00:19:42.614
but it doesn't mean that
you're being restricted

00:19:42.647 --> 00:19:44.816
because of accessibility.

00:19:44.849 --> 00:19:47.285
Christina: Exactly, and
that--I mean, I've learned

00:19:47.318 --> 00:19:51.523
something like that too, that
sometimes we need the box

00:19:51.556 --> 00:19:55.060
to be more creative, right?

00:19:55.093 --> 00:19:57.629
The more you know about
the box that you're in,

00:19:57.662 --> 00:19:59.664
the more creative you can get.

00:19:59.697 --> 00:20:02.334
So absolutely, it helps.

00:20:02.367 --> 00:20:04.169
Mike: Cool, well,
going to do some questions.

00:20:04.202 --> 00:20:06.338
Our first question
is, "For businesses,

00:20:06.371 --> 00:20:10.342
what is the easiest fix or win
for making an e-commerce

00:20:10.375 --> 00:20:13.211
site more accessible?"

00:20:13.244 --> 00:20:15.680
Christina: And
that's a good question.

00:20:15.713 --> 00:20:19.651
I mean, ultimately, it
depends on how accessible

00:20:19.684 --> 00:20:22.220
your site already is.

00:20:22.253 --> 00:20:25.423
But one of the biggest things
that I think a lot of people

00:20:25.456 --> 00:20:29.127
miss out on when
considering accessibility,

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:32.430
sort of just trying to do
these quick and easy fixes,

00:20:32.463 --> 00:20:37.068
is focusing on those contact
forms, making sure that you can

00:20:37.101 --> 00:20:40.238
back tab in them, that you can
get into them with the mouse

00:20:40.271 --> 00:20:44.442
or with the keyboard or with
the screen reader or however

00:20:44.475 --> 00:20:47.579
somebody might need to access
your form, making sure that

00:20:47.612 --> 00:20:52.784
they can get into it, they can
move around in it, they

00:20:52.817 --> 00:20:58.523
know always what the fields are
that they're typing into, and

00:20:58.556 --> 00:21:02.827
that it's easy for
them to submit.

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:06.665
Mike: Okay, our next
question is, "Do you have

00:21:06.698 --> 00:21:09.801
suggestions for tools people
can use to stop or

00:21:09.834 --> 00:21:14.105
block annoying autoplaying
sound and video?"

00:21:14.138 --> 00:21:17.342
Christina: Oh,
that's an awesome question.

00:21:17.375 --> 00:21:21.479
I do not, but now, I didn't even
think to look for something like

00:21:21.512 --> 00:21:24.149
that because
literally, I wasn't joking.

00:21:24.182 --> 00:21:27.752
I update sites every
week as part of my job,

00:21:27.785 --> 00:21:31.122
and there's one site that
has a video that autoplays,

00:21:31.155 --> 00:21:33.391
and it's quite down
on the screen too.

00:21:33.424 --> 00:21:37.195
And every single
week, it scares me.

00:21:37.228 --> 00:21:38.763
Every single week.

00:21:38.796 --> 00:21:43.601
So I am going to look into that
and see if I can find something

00:21:43.634 --> 00:21:47.739
that I'm going to use, and
then I'll update the answer

00:21:47.772 --> 00:21:50.775
on the website when I do.

00:21:50.808 --> 00:21:55.246
Mike: Excellent; so on a
similar vein, 'cause, you know,

00:21:55.279 --> 00:21:58.350
some people are, you
know, we're on a WordPress,

00:21:58.383 --> 00:22:00.085
you know,
Accessibility Day, so obviously,

00:22:00.118 --> 00:22:02.120
we're making our
WordPress sites accessible,

00:22:02.153 --> 00:22:05.256
but not everybody
uses the WordPress CMS.

00:22:05.289 --> 00:22:07.392
Do you think any of
the out-of-the-box,

00:22:07.425 --> 00:22:10.061
like turnkey solutions that do
work with WordPress but also

00:22:10.094 --> 00:22:12.430
things like
Shopify or Wix or Weebly,

00:22:12.463 --> 00:22:14.466
like AudioEye or any
of those, you know,

00:22:14.499 --> 00:22:18.636
application SAS
accessibility services,

00:22:18.669 --> 00:22:22.173
have any value, or do you think
it should--the site should just

00:22:22.206 --> 00:22:26.711
be natively accessible from the
beginning of the design process?

00:22:26.744 --> 00:22:28.680
Christina: I mean, I do
believe the more natively

00:22:28.713 --> 00:22:32.550
accessible it is, the better.

00:22:32.583 --> 00:22:35.353
Starting with that foundation,
you know, when--again, people

00:22:35.386 --> 00:22:39.057
talk about how much it costs to
make a site accessible, it's

00:22:39.090 --> 00:22:41.559
actually one of those
retrofitting issues, right?

00:22:41.592 --> 00:22:46.698
It's more costly to retrofit
accessibility into your existing

00:22:46.731 --> 00:22:50.835
site than to build it from the
beginning with accessibility.

00:22:50.868 --> 00:22:54.572
And when you--lots of
those things regarding

00:22:54.605 --> 00:22:58.209
accessibility don't even have
anything to do with the platform

00:22:58.242 --> 00:23:01.146
you're on, you know,
things like the contrasts

00:23:01.179 --> 00:23:02.480
of the colors that you use.

00:23:02.513 --> 00:23:04.315
Those are design
choices that need

00:23:04.348 --> 00:23:05.483
to be made from the beginning.

00:23:05.516 --> 00:23:09.387
So anything and everything
you can do to start from a good

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:12.557
place of accessibility
from the very beginning

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:15.560
is the best way to go.

00:23:15.593 --> 00:23:17.228
Mike: Okay, excellent.

00:23:17.261 --> 00:23:19.664
So I'm not seeing
any other questions,

00:23:19.697 --> 00:23:23.835
so I think we are
going to wrap it up.

00:23:23.868 --> 00:23:25.570
Again, thank you
so much, Christina,

00:23:25.603 --> 00:23:31.443
for taking the time and
sharing your expertise with us.

00:23:31.476 --> 00:23:35.246
And your slides can be found
at wpaccessibilityday.org,

00:23:35.279 --> 00:23:36.781
and you're also
on Twitter, right?

00:23:36.814 --> 00:23:38.483
Christina: I am on Twitter, yes.

00:23:38.516 --> 00:23:41.319
Mike: Okay, and
what's your username?

00:23:41.352 --> 00:23:44.189
Christina: Twitter
username is amethystanswers.

00:23:44.222 --> 00:23:46.558
I will spell that because
very few people know

00:23:46.591 --> 00:23:48.126
how to spell amethyst.

00:23:48.159 --> 00:23:57.602
So that is
A-M-E-T-H-Y-S-T A-N-S-W-E-R-S.

00:23:57.635 --> 00:23:59.504
Mike: Excellent; and while
you're on Twitter, please

00:23:59.537 --> 00:24:04.075
follow us @WPAccessibility, and
our two hashtags are

00:24:04.108 --> 00:24:12.116
#wpaccessibilityday
and #wpad2020.

00:24:12.149 --> 00:24:13.685
Thank you so much for watching.

00:24:13.718 --> 00:24:16.187
Thank you to all of
our wonderful sponsors.

00:24:16.220 --> 00:24:19.157
And please stay tuned because
even though I'm out of here as

00:24:19.190 --> 00:24:22.760
your host, at the top
of the hour at 3 a.m. UTC,

00:24:22.793 --> 00:24:26.698
we have Alicia, whose topic
